defaultTo all three questions, the answer is no! Or largely no!defaultFirst, whilst the IPCC will assert time and time that it understands the climate, the simple fact is that all they 
defaultknow about the global climate is encapsulated in their models, of which not one predicted the current “pause” in global temperatures.
default&#xa0;
defaultSecond, as the IPCC cannot predict even the coarsest variables of the climate (temperature), it is obvious that it would be all but impossible for them to predict the finer detail of the effect of human activity, except in one respect: CO
default2
default is a greenhouse gas. Hidden in the detail of the IPCC report is a simple fact: that almost all experts (&amp; sceptics) are agreed that the greenhouse effect of CO
default2
default would cause about 1C rise in global temperature for a doubling over a century. However this good science is a small part of the theory of what is called “global warming”. As the cover image shows, the greenhouse effect of CO
default2
default does not explain 20
defaultth
default century warming nor does it support the vast bulk of IPCC predictions on temperature or climate.
default&#xa0;
defaultThird, using standard economic scenarios (not dreamt up figures of discount rates as used by Stern), even at the very highest predicted rates of warming, the costs of any action far outweighs the harm done: to the economy by removing cheap energy; to society through rise fuel bills and rising winter deaths, and to the environment by the industrialisation of the countryside through windmills which many rightly call “bird 
defaultmincers
default”.
defaultThe reason why the IPCC fail to understand climate is very simple. As an electronic engineer I understand that even the simplest component in the simplest circuit has noise. This is true of the climate, but  ...
default… the IPCC do not understand noise or natural variation.defaultAnd as a result, and unlike any real system or models used by the engineers who understand the real world is full of noise, the climate models do not include within them any concept of noise. How can this be? The real world is full of noise, but not the climate models! 
default&#xa0;
defaultBut, natural variation or noise was stated in the first IPCC report as the null hypothesis:
default&#xa0;
defaultWe take a conservative view as a starting point namely that the magnitude of natural variability is such that all of the warming of the past century could be attributed to this cause (Note that this is not the same as denying the existence of an enhanced greenhouse effect)
