default 11.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEven if the benefits exceed the cost, what is the opportunity cost?default 
defaultCould we spend the money of better things like e.g. a cure for cancer. In other words, would future generations prefer we had invested in a cure for cancer or trying to reduce warming?
default&#xa0;
default 12.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAnd lastly even if it’s financially a good idea, is it morally right?default 
defaultIs it right that the poorest in society are for example denied fuel in Scotland where there are estimates that 50% are in fuel poverty. Is it right that we ask the poor of today to sacrifice in order to make the richer part of the richer society of the future even richer?
defaultAnd what if the real solution were found to be to cut the world population? A logical solution would be for us all to continue using the same amount of fossil fuel but cut the number of people. But would it be morally right to e.g. sterilise a significant proportion of women to prevent population growth? 
defaultAre there some things where morality means we have to put up with minor problems like some small amounts of warming even if there is an overall benefit to society from acting?
